5. The circuit of claim 1, wherein the amplitude control circuit comprises: 
a program counter configured to generate a timing signal based on the predefined frequency, the timing signal having a plurality of clock pulses; 
a peak detector configured to generate a first digital word corresponding to the current amplitude of the output signal of the oscillator; 
a digital comparator configured to compare the first digital word to a second digital word associated with the predefined amplitude; and 
logic configured to receive the timing signal and, in response to each of the plurality of clock pulses, to generate the plurality of control signals based on the comparison of the first digital word to the second digital word.

11. A method for maintaining the amplitude of an output signal of a controllable oscillator at a predefined amplitude level, the controllable oscillator having a plurality of operational states, each of the plurality of operational states corresponding to a particular current bias and defining a distinct amplitude for the output signal of the controllable oscillator, comprising: 
determining the current amplitude of the output signal of the controllable oscillator, the current amplitude corresponding to a current operational state; 
comparing the predefined amplitude level to the current amplitude; 
if the current amplitude is less than the predefined amplitude level, based on the comparing the predefined amplitude level to the current amplitude, selecting one of two next operational states, the selected next operational state having a distinct amplitude that better approximates the predefined amplitude level.

20. A system for maintaining the amplitude of an output signal of a controllable oscillator at a predefined amplitude level, the controllable oscillator having a plurality of operational states, each of the plurality of operational states corresponding to a particular current bias and defining a distinct amplitude for the output signal of the controllable oscillator, comprising: 
means for determining the current amplitude of the output signal of the controllable oscillator, the current amplitude corresponding to a current operational state; 
means for comparing the predefined amplitude level to the current amplitude; 
means for selecting, when the current amplitude is less than the predefined amplitude level, one of two next operational states based on the comparing the predefined amplitude level to the current amplitude, the selected next operational state having a distinct amplitude which better approximates the predefined amplitude level.
